<blockquote>
<p>&#1605;&#1581;&#1605;&#1608;&#1583; &#1576;&#1585;&#1575;&#1583;&#1585;&#1605; &#1588;&#1583; &#1588;&#1740;&#1585; &#1605;&#1705;&#1740;&#1606;<br>
&#1605;&#1740;&#1705;&#1585;&#1583; &#1582;&#1589;&#1608;&#1605;&#1578; &#1575;&#1586; &#1662;&#1740; &#1578;&#1575;&#1580; &#1608; &#1606;&#1711;&#1740;&#1606;<br>
&#1705;&#1585;&#1583;&#1740;&#1605; &#1583;&#1608; &#1576;&#1582;&#1588; &#1578;&#1575; &#1576;&#1585; &#1570;&#1587;&#1575;&#1740;&#1583; &#1582;&#1604;&#1602;<br>
&#1575;&#1608; &#1586;&#1605;&#1740;&#1606; &#1711;&#1585;&#1601;&#1578; &#1608; &#1605;&#1606; &#1585;&#1608;&#1740; &#1586;&#1605;&#1740;&#1606;</p>
<p><em>Mahm&ucirc;d bar&acirc;dar-am shod shir-e makin,<br /></em><em>Mikard kho&#7779;umat az pay-ye t&acirc;j o nagin.<br /></em><em>Kardim do bakhsh t&acirc; bar &acirc;s&acirc;yad khalq,<br /></em><em>U zir zamin gereft o man ruy-e zamin</em>.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>In E.G. Browne&rsquo;s translation:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>My brother Ma&#7717;m&ucirc;d, lion-like crouched low,<br />For crown and ring was my relentless foe.<br />At length we shared the earth that men might rest:<br />I took the surface, he the realm below. (<em>Literary History</em> 3.166-67)</p>
</blockquote>
<p>The Iranian poet L&acirc;huti wrote a famous poem in 1923 which described the 1917 revolution in Russia as a <em>zalzala</em> (Persian <em>zelzeleh</em>), an earthquake:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>&#1606;&#1575;&#1711;&#1575;&#1607; <strong>&#1586;&#1605;&#1740;&#1606;</strong> &#1604;&#1585;&#1586;&#1740;&#1583; &#1608;&#1586; &#1583;&#1608;&#1585; &#1601;&#1604;&#1705; &#1578;&#1585;&#1587;&#1740;&#1583;<br />&#1670;&#1608;&#1606; &#1583;&#1575;&#1583; &#1583;&#1585;&#1601;&#1588; &#1587;&#1585;&#1582; &#1576;&#1585; &#1605;&#1581;&#1608; &#1587;&#1578;&#1605; &#1601;&#1585;&#1605;&#1575;&#1606;</p>
<p><em>N&acirc;g&acirc;h </em><strong><em>zamin</em></strong><em> larzid va-z d&ucirc;r falak tarsid<br /></em><em>chun d&acirc;d derafsh-e sorkh bar ma&#7717;v-e setam farm&acirc;n</em>.</p>
<p>[Suddenly the earth (<em>zam&icirc;n</em>) trembled, and dreaded the vicissitudes of the sky (i.e. of fate) when the red banner commanded the extinction of tyranny. (translated by Munibur Rahman, in <em>Post-Revolution Persian Verse</em>, 157-58)]</p>
</blockquote>
<p>A <em>ri&#7717;la</em> (previous chapter) is one way to cross the surface of the <em>zamin</em>. A <em>ziy&acirc;ra </em>is another, a more goal-oriented ambulation, a visit to a friend or a pilgrimage.</p>
<p>The stem of <em>Ziy&acirc;ra</em> is Z-W-R, to visit. It's the stem which gives us <em>maz&acirc;r</em>, the goal of a <em>ziy&acirc;ra</em>. This is the <em>maz&acirc;r </em>of Mazar-e Sharif in Afghanistan. The specific <em>maz&acirc;r</em> in Mazar-e Sharif is Al-masjid al-Azraq. (An apocryphal story says that the Prophet&rsquo;s nephew Ali is buried there. More likely he&rsquo;s buried in Najaf.) <em>Al-masjid al-Azraq</em> is &ldquo;the blue mosque.&rdquo; (It isn&rsquo;t the only one: the Sultan Ahmad mosque in Istanbul [<em>Sultanahmet camii</em>] is also sometimes referred to as the Blue Mosque.) The Arabic stem for <em>azraq</em> Z-R-Q is to be blue. Th<strong>e </strong>blue of the sky is <em>zarq&acirc;&rsquo;</em>. One adjective form is Azraq&icirc;, as in Abu Bakr Azraqi, the quick-witted poet at the court of &#7788;ugh&acirc;n Sh&acirc;h.</p>
<p>A stopping place for travelers was often a <em>z&acirc;wiya</em>, a Sufi meeting place that often doubled as a guest house. Ibn Ba&#7789;&#7789;u&#7789;a used <em>zaw&acirc;y&acirc;</em> (the plural form) throughout his travels, as a kind of hostel. They were at one time the logical substitute for a hotel, at least if you belonged to a Sufi order. Etymologically a <em>z&acirc;wiya</em> is also a corner (or an angle in mathematics), and it is with this meaning that the form <em>inziw&acirc;</em> came into Persian as a loan word, <em>enzev&acirc;</em>, meaning solitude, isolation. Beta Virginis, the second brightest star in Virgo, is in Europe Zavijava, which traces back, inexplicably, to the name <em>Z&acirc;wiyat al-&lsquo;aw&acirc;&rsquo;</em>, &#1586;&#1575;&#1608;&#1740;&#1577; &#1575;&#1604;&#1593;&#1608;&#1575;&#1569;, the corner of the dogs, meaning the dog kennel. The fifth brightest is Zaniah, which also comes from <em>z&acirc;wiya</em> but without the puzzle.</p>
<p>Two Za words are planets: Zo&#7717;al, Saturn, and Zuhra, Venus. In Iranian pre-Islamic cosmology Zuhra started out as a beautiful woman: the giants Harut and Marut fell in love with her and gave her the secret word that would allow her to rise into heaven. The source of Zo&#7717;al is simpler, just the Arabic stem Z-&#7716;-L, to withdraw, move away, perhaps because, before the discovery of the planet we know as Neptune, Saturn was the furthest away and slowest moving of visible planets. In <em>Star Trek</em> Zahl is a star and a culture who comes from The Delta Quadrant of the Milky Way. They were destroyed in Season four of Star Trek The Next Generation.</p>
