<h3>Life Science</h3>
<p>Two Za words take a prominent place in one of the most celebrated passages of the Qur`&acirc;n, the <em>Mishk&acirc;t al-anw&acirc;r</em> or &ldquo;Niche of Lights&rdquo; passage of the sura called &ldquo;N&ucirc;r,&rdquo; &ldquo;Light&rdquo; (the sura is named after this passage). It takes the form of a prolonged metaphor, in which God&rsquo;s light is given a <em>mathal</em>, a figurative explication:&nbsp;</p>
<blockquote>
<p>The parable of His Light [<em>mathalu n&ucirc;rihi</em>]<br />Is as if there were a niche<br />And within it a lamp [<em>misb&acirc;h</em>]<br />The lamp enclosed in glass [<strong>&#1586;&#1580;&#1575;&#1580;&#1577;</strong> <em>zuj&acirc;ja</em>]<br />The glass as it were<br />A brilliant star:<br />Lit from a blessed tree,<br />An olive [<strong>&#1586;&#1740;&#1578;&#1608;&#1606;&#1577; </strong><em>zayt&ucirc;na</em>], neither of the east<br />Nor of the west<br />whose oil [<strong>&#1586;&#1740;&#1578;</strong> <em>zayt</em>] is well-nigh luminous,<br />though fire scarce touched it . . . (24.35, Yusuf Ali trans.)</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Even in translation it is easy to see why this passage has been so widely memorized and admired. A domestic, simple household scene, easy to visualize, is used to portray the highest possible vision. There has even been a book-length analysis of this passage (by the eleventh-century mystical scholar Ab&ucirc; H&acirc;mid al-Ghaz&acirc;l&icirc;).</p>
<p>Al-Ghaz&acirc;l&icirc; traces the steps of perception: Za word <em>zuj&acirc;ja</em> (glass) stands between us and the source of radiance. The oil (<em>zayt</em>) of the<em> zayt&ucirc;na</em> (the olive tree) is the source of the light, lit by fuel neither of the east or the west, which means, I suppose, that it is not confined to the earth. It is as if each image added an additional intermediary between human perception and the source of light.&nbsp;</p>
<p>The <em>Zayt&ucirc;na</em> has much the same cachet in Arabic culture as in Greece, where the tree is an emblem of solidity. (Odysseus&rsquo;s bed in Ithaca is carved from a live olive tree, evidently a very big one.) The <em>mishk&acirc;t al-anw&acirc;r</em> locates the olive near the center of the divine vision. When olive orchards are destroyed in the West Bank there are many reasons to be angry, but the feeling that, in the Qur&rsquo;&acirc;n, there is something noumenous in the plant itself can only give that pain an additional edge.</p>
<p class="illo"><img src="../_img/za7.png" width="350" align="right" style="margin-right:-80px" /></p>
<p>There is an upscale confectionary in Amman named Zanjabil. It&rsquo;s where I first became aware of the word. Among Za words Zanjabil seems to have had a particularly wide geographical spread. It is a delicacy of both the east and the west. Arabic folk etymology considers <em>zanjab&icirc;l</em> a plant from Zanzibar. Dictionary etymologies point out that <em>Zanjab&icirc;l</em> shares the z-sound with the Greek <em>zigg&iacute;beris</em>, ginger. Latin kept the Z when it borrowed the word as <em>zingiber</em> (Italian <em>zenzero</em>), but further west it thickens to the G of Portugese <em>gingibre</em> &mdash; or English ginger. (Europe started importing it early; the OED lists a use of the word in English as far back as 1000 CE.) It gets a positive reference in the Qur&rsquo;&acirc;n. A drink of some sort mixed with ginger is offered to residents of heaven (Q 76.17).</p>
<p>(To the east, where the word is rooted, it begins with the sh- sound, as in Middle Persian <em>shangav&icirc;r</em> and Sanskrit <em>sri&ntilde;gavera</em>, which Yule in <em>Hobson-Jobson</em> wrangles to the ground by identifying a visible etymology <em>sri&ntilde;ga</em>, &ldquo;horn.&rdquo; The Humez brothers, in their book on the Roman alphabet, translate &ldquo;horn-body.&rdquo;)</p>
<p>There is a famously tedious story in <em>The Canterbury Tales</em>, the story of Sir Thopas, which is set just across the channel in Flanders, told so badly that the other pilgrims cut him off after a handful of stanzas. We don&rsquo;t learn much about the hero beyond his place of birth (&ldquo;Yborn he was in fer contree, / In Flaundres. Al biyonde the see . . .&rdquo;) and that he has the complexion of a local boy: &ldquo;His heer, his berd was lyk saffroun.&rdquo; Saffron is in the Arab word <em>za&lsquo;afr&acirc;n</em>, proverbial for the deep yellow or orange color of the pistils (the petals are purple). Sir Thopaz&rsquo;s hair is no doubt either red or very blonde, tending towards orange. <em>Za&lsquo;afr&acirc;n</em> may or may not be an Arabic word originally, but you can feel the Arabic form behind all the European loan words. Spanish <em>azafran</em> carries the traces of the Arabic definite article, <em>al-za&lsquo;afr&acirc;n</em>. Italian <em>zafferano </em>keeps the Z sound.</p>
<p>The Arabic stem <em>Z &ndash;R -&lsquo;</em>Ayn is to sow or spread, and the vocabulary of agriculture (<em>zar&acirc;&lsquo;a</em>) derives from it. &ldquo;Flower&rdquo; is also a Za-word in Arabic: <em>zahr</em> (from Z-H-R, the stem for &ldquo;to shine, to give light&rdquo;). The name of the major theological university in Cairo, Al-Azh&acirc;r, comes from that stem. A flower among universities.</p>
<p>Hardly any flower names start with Z in English. (The exceptions are &ldquo;zinnia,&rdquo; named for an 18th-century biologist named Gottfried Zinn, and a root named zedoary, which somewhere or other is traced back to Persian <em>jadv&acirc;r</em>, a word I can&rsquo;t locate in any dictionary.) Elsewhere Z seems the default letter for flowers. A <em>zanbaq</em> is in Persian an iris. A <em>zab&icirc;b </em>is in Arabic a raisin. (In an etymology I cannot explain, <em>zab&icirc;b</em> seems to derive from <em>zibb</em>, a word for penis.) Meanwhile, a <em>zab&icirc;ba</em> is the mark on the forehead caused by the repeated pressure of intense prayer. A <em>zereshk</em> in Persian is a barberry. Yellow plants may have the color (<em>zard</em>) in the name. A <em>zard&acirc;l&ucirc;</em> is an apricot. A <em>zardak </em>is a carrot; <em>zardchubeh</em> is turmeric.</p>
<p>You can see a theme, a lot of Za words in a packed world of growing and animate beings. A <em>zur&acirc;fa</em> is a giraffe. A crow is a <em>z&acirc;gh</em>. The Arabic verb <em>zarzara</em> means to chirp, and in its noun form, <em>zurz&ucirc;r</em>, it means &ldquo;starling.&rdquo; The Arabic verb <em>Zaqzaqa</em>, to peep, chirp, but also to feed, gives us a noun form <em>zuqz&ucirc;q</em>, a lapwing. (In its plural form, Zaq&acirc;z&icirc;q, it is the name of a city in the Nile Delta.) A <em>zanbur</em> in Persian and in Arabic is a bee.</p>
<p><em>Zendeg&icirc; </em>in Persian is &ldquo;life.&rdquo; <em>Zendeh</em> is &ldquo;alive.&rdquo; In Arabic <em>z&acirc;da</em> (Z-Y-D) is the verb for growth and increase&mdash;thus Arabic <em>ziy&acirc;da</em>, surplus or addition, and in Persian a loan word, <em>ziy&acirc;d</em>, &ldquo;a lot.&rdquo; Zinedine Zidane&rsquo;s name (known to fans as Zizou) is from the same stem. &ldquo;Zayd&icirc;n&icirc; `ishqan,&rdquo; the song by the great Lebanese poet Nizar Qabbani, made popular by the Iraqi singer K&acirc;zem Al-S&acirc;hir, shows the imperative of the same verb: &ldquo;Increase your love for me.&rdquo; You can find it on YouTube and below the screen you find one enthusiastic fan who compares it to a <em>zalz&acirc;l</em>, a shock like an earthquake.</p>
<p>The source of living things is also a Za word. The stem Z-W-J, meaning &ldquo;to combine,&rdquo; &ldquo;put in pairs,&rdquo; gives us <em>izdiv&acirc;j</em>, &ldquo;marriage,&rdquo; <em>zawja</em>, &ldquo;wife&rdquo; and <em>zawj</em> (Turkish <em>zev&ccedil;</em>), &ldquo;husband.&rdquo; As for offspring, it is probably a coincidence that the Persian verb <em>z&acirc;dan</em>, to give birth, resembles the Arabic words for increase. <em>Z&acirc;dan</em>, the Persian verb, occurs pretty frequently in its passive participle form, &ndash;-<em>z&acirc;deh</em>. It&rsquo;s the suffix in Persian proper names, for &ldquo;child of&rdquo; (like -<em>oghlou</em> in Turkish, -<em>ides</em> in Greek, &ndash;<em>ski</em> in Russian or -son in English, -<em>zai </em>in Pashto, as in Yousefzai).</p>
<p>The Arabic verb <em>z&acirc;na</em>, &ldquo;to decorate,&rdquo; gives us <em>zayn</em>, &ldquo;beauty,&rdquo; and <em>zayna</em>, &ldquo;ornament.&rdquo; It often refers to the aesthetic dimension of the natural world. A characteristic phrase in the Qur&rsquo;&acirc;n is 37.6 (<em>Al-Saff&acirc;t</em>): &ldquo;<em>Inn&acirc; zayn-n&acirc; al-sam&acirc;&lsquo;a al-duny&acirc; bi-zaynati al-kaw&acirc;kibi</em>.&rdquo; (&ldquo;We have indeed decked [<em>zayn&acirc;</em>] the lower heaven with beauty [<em>zayna</em>] in the stars&rdquo;&mdash;trans. Yusuf Ali.) or (multiplying Za words) a passage in the Sura of Jonah, where the rain brings forth a world of increase: &rdquo;<em>akhadhati al-ar&#7693;u zukhruf-h&acirc; wa azaynat wa&#7827;ana ahluh&acirc; </em>[until the earth is clad with its golden ornaments (<em>zukhruf</em>) and is decked out with beauty (<em>azaynat</em>)&rdquo;]&mdash; 10.24).&nbsp;</p>
<p><em>Zukhruf </em>has a negative side. It can also mean excessive decoration or empty speech. You may hear it translated empty rhetoric, bullshit, nonsense, malarkey.</em></p>
<h3>Non-Being</h3>
<p>Nietzsche was a philologist at a time when philology was a heroic enterprise, in an era of great discoveries. His first publication, <em>The Birth of Tragedy</em> (1871), came out a hundred years after the famous French translation by Anquetil-Duperron of the Zend-Avesta, the commentary on the Zoroastrian prayers (1771). In 1877, six years after <em>The Birth of Tragedy</em>, another northerner, Robert Nobel, brought his business to Central Asia. He had an interest in the Middle East, in a sense &mdash; in the sense that he had an oil interest in Azerbaijan. He developed the first oil tanker to transport oil from the Caspian to Astrachan, where one could entrust the product to the Russian train system. (This kind of oil by the way is not called <em>zayt</em>, but <em>naft</em>, probably from Greek <em>naftha</em>.) Oil has been an economic disaster for every Middle Eastern community where it has been discovered, but at least Nobel showed enough sensitivity to the local culture to name that tanker the Zoroaster. (The historical Zoroaster is said to have come from near the Caspian, the area of Lake Urmiya.)</p>
<p>Robert Nobel&rsquo;s tanker may not have influenced Nietzsche<strong>, </strong>but it was only a few years later that <em>Thus Spoke Zarathustra</em> appeared. Zoroaster is a commoner pronunciation in English (coming to us through a Greek form) but Zarathustra is closer to the Persian name, Zardosht (a variant of an earlier word Zartosht which meant etymologically something about camels, or something yellow), one of those Z&acirc; words which sends us back to Iranian antiquity. I have never heard a good explanation of why Nietzsche attributed his philosophy of 1883-85 to Zardosht, but there probably is one: Nietzsche knew a good deal about Indo-European philology: why wouldn&rsquo;t he have known Old Persian?</p>
<p>In order to refute the enlightenment vision of classical Greece, characterized by their optimism and clarity of vision, in <em>The Birth of Tragedy</em> he famously cites a story about King Midas:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>There is an ancient story that King Midas hunted in the forest a long time for the wise Silenus, the companion of Dionysus, without capturing him. When Silenus at last fell into his hands, the king asked what was the best and most desirable of all things for man. Fixed and immovable, the demigod said not a word, till at last, urged by the king, he gave a shrill laugh and broke out into these words: &ldquo;Oh, wretched ephemeral race, children of chance and misery, why do you compel me to tell you what it would be most expedient for you not to hear? What is best of all is utterly beyond your reach: not be born, not to <em>be</em>, to be <em>nothing</em>. But the second best for you is&mdash;to die soon.&rdquo; (<em>Birth of Tragedy</em>, 42)</p>
</blockquote>
<p>It is one of many stories about Midas&rsquo;s abduction of Silenus, and it has a paradoxical fascination. The idea of finding an informant with insider&rsquo;s knowledge of another world, the <em>E.T.</em> narrative, has a deep appeal. It is the unspoken mainspring of anthropology.</p>
<p>Nietzsche&rsquo;s source is an essay attributed to Plutarch, called &ldquo;Consolation to Apollonius.&rdquo; (Plutarch attributes it to Aristotle.) He could have found it elsewhere. The idea kicked around the classical world for centuries. Cicero quotes it (in a book of stoic dialogues called the <em>Tusculan Disputations</em> 1.114) as does Lactantius. Theognis (b. 540 BCE) includes among the counsels of his elegies (1.1013-16) the idea that it is better never to have been born, and the chorus of Sophocles&rsquo; <em>Oedipus at Colonus</em> repeats the same philosophy (1224-26): &ldquo;Not to be born at all is best . . . next best, once born, to turn back . . .&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>
<p>Readers of Ferdowsi&rsquo;s <em>Sh&acirc;hn&acirc;ma</em>, that great verse narrative of narratives from the days before Islam, will encounter the character Zarir, who died defending the new faith of Zardosht [<em>Zartosht</em>]. It&rsquo;s his brother King Gosht&acirc;sb who asks the sorcerer J&acirc;m&acirc;sb for advice:</p>
<blockquote>
<p><em>Mar&acirc; k&acirc;shki pish-e farrokh Zarir&nbsp;<br /></em><em>Zam&acirc;neh fekandi beh chang&acirc;l-e shir<br /></em><em>Vagar khod nakoshti pedar mar mar&acirc; . . .<br /></em><em>Nagashti beh J&acirc;m&acirc;sp bad akhtr&acirc;</em></p>
<p>[&ldquo;I would that in the presence of the blessed Zarir / destiny (<em>zam&acirc;neh</em>) had cast me into the claws of a lion, / or that my father had slain me before a baleful star had been destined for J&acirc;m&acirc;sb.&rdquo; (Reuben Levy trans., 195)]&nbsp;</p>
</blockquote>
<p>There is an earlier version of the same story in the heroic narrative entitled <em>Aiy&acirc;dg&acirc;r-e Zarir&acirc;n</em>, dating from the 5th century BCE. The informant is the same J&acirc;m&acirc;sb, answering a slightly different question. Visht&acirc;spa/ Gosht&acirc;sb asks which of his sons and brothers will die in an impending battle against non-Zoroastrians. J&acirc;m&acirc;sb replies in a series of formulas apologizing for the bad news. One of them is familiar to us: &ldquo;Fortunate is he who is not born of his mother, or if born dies immediately or to whom the measure of long duration has not reached&rdquo; (trans. Modi,19). J&acirc;m&acirc;sb is not the source of Nietzsche&rsquo;s Silenus, but we recognize the sentiment. Freddy Mercury, who sang, in &ldquo;Bohemian Rhapsody,&rdquo; &ldquo;I don't wanna die / I sometimes wish / I was never been born at all&rdquo; was born a Zoroastrian, but it seems unlikely that&rsquo;s the reason he wrote those lines.</p>
<p>There is another passage in &ldquo;The Birth of Tragedy&rdquo; where Nietzsche approaches the limits of human experience, this time from a different angle. It has to do with the music of Wagner. There is a part of the opera <em>Tristan and Isolde,</em> he suggests, that draws us out of ourselves, that makes us long to escape the melancholy glass enclosure of human individuality (&ldquo;<em>in der elenden gl&auml;sernen H&uuml;lle des menschlichen Individuums</em>&rdquo;). It is an extreme way to describe the power of the arts to take us outside ourselves, really outside ourselves. Passages like this may be the reason for a surprising judgment on Nietzsche in a great poem in Persian by the Indo-Persian poet Muhammad Iqbal (1877-1938).</p>
<p>Iqbal wrote in both Urdu and Persian. His most celebrated work in Persian is a 1932 verse narrative, based on Dante&rsquo;s <em>Divine Comedy</em>, in which the poet Rumi plays the Virgil role, leading Iqbal on a tour of the afterlife. It is at a high level in the itinerary, beyond the sphere of Zoa&#7717;al (Saturn) that they encounter a presence, a suffering soul with &ldquo;a voice full of agony&rdquo; (<em>&#7779;ad&acirc;-ye dardmand</em>). It is <strong>&#1606;&#1591;&#1588;&#1607;</strong>, <em>Ne&#7789;sheh</em>, Nietzsche, whose reed pipe contains an ancient melody, who saw the same glimpses of reality that the great mystics saw, but &ldquo;There was none in Europe who knew the Way&rdquo; (<em>Mard-e rah d&acirc;ni na-budand andar Farang</em>). In the absence of a Sufi path, he didn&rsquo;t know how to deal with the experience, and that glimpse drove him insane.&nbsp;</p>
<blockquote>
<p>&#1605;&#1587;&#1578;&#1740; &#1575;&#1608; &#1607;&#1585; &#1580;&#1580;&#1575;&#1580;&#1740; &#1585;&#1575; &#1588;&#1705;&#1587;&#1578;<br />&#1575;&#1586; &#1582;&#1583;&#1575; &#1576;&#1576;&#1585;&#1740;&#1583; &#1608; &#1607;&#1605; &#1575;&#1586; &#1582;&#1608;&#1583; &#1711;&#1587;&#1587;&#1578;<br /><br /><em>Masti-ye u har </em><strong><em>zuj&acirc;ji</em></strong><em> r&acirc; shekast</em><em><br /></em><em>Az Khod&acirc; bobrid-o ham az khowd gosast.</em></p>
<p>[His drunkenness shattered every glass./He cut himself off from God and split off from himself. (Or... His intoxication shattered every glass; He broke from God, and was snapped too from himself. &ndash;trans. A.J. Arberry)]</p>
</blockquote>
<p>It&rsquo;s a symmetrical relationship: Nietzsche turned to an Iranian prophet for a mouthpiece to articulate his own late philosophy. In return, it&rsquo;s only fair that Nietzsche was absorbed into a mystical epic written in Persian. No doubt Iqbal had in mind the <em>zujaj </em>in the 24th sura of the Qur&rsquo;&acirc;n, the pane of glass which represents the intermediary between humans and the other world. No doubt he was also alluding to the passage in <em>The Birth of Tragedy</em> where Nietzsche speaks of the soul trapped in the glass bell of its individuality.&nbsp;</p>

